s in Domesday Book as <i>Belintone</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of <i>Billa</i>’; the one in Bedfordshire is recorded in 1196 as <i>Billendon</i>, from an Old English personal name <i>Billa</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. The place in Lancashire is the most likely source of the surname.","History: John Billington (1580–1630), from Spalding, Lincolnshire, was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620 and an early settler in Plymouth Colony. Governor Bradford called him ‘the profanest’ of the settlers; eventually he was hanged for murder. His son Francis married and had children."],"variants":[{"name":"Bullington","meanings":["English:","variant of   Billington  , found as such in colonial VA.","habitational name from Bullington in Lincolnshire, named in Old English ‘the settlement (<i>tūn</i>) associated with (connective particle <i>-ing</i>) a man named <i>Bula</i>’. Alternatively, a variant of <b>Bollington</b>, a habitational name from Bollington in Cheshire, named in Old English ‘the settlement (<i>tūn</i>) on the river Bolling’. This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bill","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Bille</i> or <i>Bile</i>, either a pet form of the female names <i>Amabil</i> and <i>Sybil</i> or a survival of Old English <i>Bil</i> or Old Norse <i>Bildr</i>.","English: nickname from Middle English (Old English) <i>bile</i> ‘bill, beak (of a bird)’, perhaps used contemptuously of a person's nose or mouth. It may also be an occupational name from Middle English (Old English) <i>bil(l)</i> ‘bill(hook), pruning hook, halberd’, given perhaps to a user or maker of pruning hooks and similar implements. See   Biller   5.","English: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a promontory or headland, from Middle English <i>bile</i>, <i>bille</i> ‘beak’ (from Old English <i>bile</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Birlington was born in 1430, in Cholsey, Berkshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Richard Birlingto